04447nam a22006015i 9780292767317DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212014txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927673177 a10.7560/7455442doi  a(DE-B1597)587598  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aML421.F558b.D38 2014eb 7aMUS0170002bisacsh04a781.642092/22231 aDavis, John T., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Flatlanders :bNow It's Now Again /cJohn T. Davis. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE: The Land -- tChapter 1: The Llano -- tChapter 2: The City -- tChapter 3: The Invasion -- tChapter 4: The House -- tPart Two: The Men, First Verse -- tChapter 5: Joe, Jimmie, and Butch, Part 1 -- tChapter 6: Compañeros -- tPart Three: The Music -- tChapter 7: Genesis -- tChapter 8: More a Legend -- tChapter 9: Diaspora -- tPart Four: The Men, Second Verse -- tChapter 10: Joe, Jimmie, and Butch, Part 2 -- tPart Five: The Return -- tChapter 11: More a Band -- tChapter 12: Alchemy: Now Again -- tChapter 13: Cruising Speed: Wheels of Fortune and Live ’72 -- tChapter 14: Dust to Dust: Hills and Valleys -- tChapter 15: Closing the Circle: Th e Odessa Tapes -- tEpilogue: Carnegie Hall: Practice, Practice, Practice -- tDiscography0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA group of three friends who made music in a house in Lubbock, Texas, recorded an album that wasn’t released and went their separate ways into solo careers. That group became a legend and then—twenty years later—a band. The Flatlanders—Joe Ely, Jimmie Dale Gilmore, and Butch Hancock—are icons in American music, with songs blending country, folk, and rock that have influenced a long list of performers, including Robert Earl Keen, the Cowboy Junkies, Ryan Bingham, Terry Allen, John Hiatt, Hayes Carll, Lucinda Williams, Steve Earle, and Lyle Lovett. In The Flatlanders: Now It’s Now Again, Austin author and music journalist John T. Davis traces the band’s musical journey from the house on 14th Street in Lubbock to their 2013 sold-out concert at Carnegie Hall. He explores why music was, and is, so important in Lubbock and how earlier West Texas musicians such as Buddy Holly and Roy Orbison, as well as a touring Elvis Presley, inspired the young Ely, Gilmore, and Hancock. Davis vividly recreates the Lubbock countercultural scene that brought the Flatlanders together and recounts their first year (1972–1973) as a band, during which they recorded the songs that, decades later, were released as the albums More a Legend Than a Band and The Odessa Tapes. He follows the three musicians through their solo careers and into their first decade as a (re)united band, in which they cowrote songs for the first time on the albums Now Again and Hills and Valleys and recovered their extraordinary original demo tape, lost for forty years. Many roads later, the Flatlanders are finally both a legend and a band.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aCountry music groupszTexaszLubbock. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Folk & Traditional.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292767317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292767317/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK